" {XPPMATH 20 "6$$\"+++++?!\"*$\"\"%\"\"!" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 95 "A. The g4 function is positive from( positive infinity to
 2): and from (4 to positive infinity)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 306 38 "kp - Why from positive infinity to 2
??" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 43 "B.  The g4 function is negative f
rom (2, 4)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "subs(x=0,g4);
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#\"$G\"" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 135 "  E.   The values for the polynomial will be arbitrarily
 large in a positive direction when the x value is very small and very
 large.  " }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 841 "3.  Polynomials:  Local \+
extreme values and monotonicity.  Beyond information of the type gathe
red above about intercepts and signs of a polynomial,  other important
 information can be determined from the so called \"critical points\" \+
of a polynomial.  The critical points of a polynomial are the intercep
ts of its derivative.  Since the derivative of a function at a point r
epresents the slope of the tangent line to the graph of the that funct
ion at the point, then the intercepts of the derivative are places whe
re the the tangent lines to the function are flat, i.e., are horizonta
l lines.  At such places the graph is neither increasing nor decreasin
g.  Elsewhere the graph must be either increasing or decreasing.  For \+
a polynomial, local extreme values (local maximums or local minimums) \+
must occur at the intercepts of the derivative.  " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 80 "     The follwing feature
s are important in analyzing the graph of a polynomial:" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 41 "     f.   critical p
oints of the function" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 99 "                \+
      For a polynomial these are the intercepts of the derivative of t
he polynomial" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     g.    local maximum
 points of the graph of a function y = f(x)" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
-1 274 "                      These are points (x,y) on the graph of t
he function for which the y-value is locally the largest value of the \+
function.  Nearby values on the graph are lower.  For a polynomials th
e x-value of the point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomia
l." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 67 "     h.   local minimum points of t
he graph of a function y = f(x) " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 276 "    \+
                  These are points (x,y) on the graph of the function \+
for which the y-value is locally the smallest value of the function.  \+
Nearby values on the graph are higher.  For a polynomials the x-value \+
of the point (x,y) must be a critical point of the polynomial." }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     i.    regions (intervals) in the do
main of the function where the values of the function are increasing" 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those regions w
here the graph rises as the graph is traversed from left to right.  Fo
r a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, these regi
ons are bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- infinity
." }}{PARA 257 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 108 "     j.    regions (intervals) in
 the domain of the function where the values of the function are decre
asing" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 249 "                       Those re
gions where the graph falls as the graph is traversed from left to rig
ht.  For a continuous function, and in particular for polynomials, the
se regions are bounded by the critical points and may stretch to +/- i
nfinity." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
275 "For each of the following polynomials,  provide a graph of the po
lynomial.  Choose a range that will optimally represent the features o
f the graph.  Include the graph of the deriviative of the polynomial o
n the plot.   Plot the function in red and the derviative in green.   \+
" }{TEXT 269 4 "Also" }{TEXT -1 89 ", for each polynomial find each of
 the above ten graphcial characteristics (a.  thru j.):" }}{PARA 0 "" 
0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 4 "a.  " }{XPPEDIT 18 0 
"y = x^2-2*x-15;" "6#/%\"yG,(*$%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"*&F(F)F'F)!\"\"\"#:F+" 
}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "g5:=(x^2-2*x-15);" }}
{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%#g5G,(*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F**&F)F*F(F
